@NODE "NEW" "Changes since v1.0"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}Major/Minor Changes/additions/bugs removed in Smarty v1.11:@{ub}

     -Added support to the locale.library: Catalan and spanish
              catalogs included (built-in english catalog).
     
     -Smarty's window is now an AppWindow. Just drop workbench icons
              on it to easily change current dir.
     
     -Added 'View' function: See 'How does it works' and 'Tooltypes'.
     
     -Configurable via Tooltypes: See 'Tooltypes'.
     
     -Added a 'Create Dir' button.

     -The 'Copy' function is now built-in, not done using 'C:Copy' as
              before. This should make copying files faster (up to 4
              times faster when copying a lof of small files).
              Copy-buffer is user configurable.

     -Using 'Move' across two dirs of the same volume causes Smarty to use
              Rename() instead of copying and then deleting. This makes
              moving in such cases very very fast.

     -Directories are now (re)readed only when needed.

     -Strings longer than a given number will be clipped, so no
              super-extra-large requesters will appear.
              (ex: 'work:foo/bar/blerk/blurp/hello/file.001' -> 
                   'work:f...lo/file.001' )

     -Now the ASL requester opened by Copy/Move functions is in SAVE
              mode. This allows you to easily create new dirs by
              simply typing a name of a dir that doesn't exist in
              the requester. It will be created.

     -Duplication can now be stopped at any time.

     -ASL requester now remembers it's last position/size (I forgot
              this because I use ASL.library v42, and the reqs always
              appeared centered in the screen. Sorry).

     -No spaces between buttons, so Smarty's GUI fits better in a
              640x200 screen.

     -MUI 3.2 help bubbles -> Now Smarty requires MUI 3.2+.
     
     -No more '060 nice guru meditations (1.11).

     -Some small bugs fixed.
@ENDNODE

@NODE "TOOL" "Configuration via Tooltypes"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}Tooltypes@{ub}

     With Smarty v1.11, it's possible to change some
settings of the program using the following Tooltypes:

     INIDIR=Dir

            This sets the default startup dir of Smarty. Defaults to SYS:.

     VIEWTOOL=Viewer

            Here you can specify the view program that Smarty uses for
            the 'View' function.
            
            If VIEWTOOL is not present, the 'View' button will be
            ghosted (-> useless).

            Smarty adds the name of the file to view at the end of the
            string you put here.
            
              sys:utilities/multiview screen|dh1:Picture.jpeg
                        TOOLTYPE            | ADDED BY SMARTY

     COPYBUF=Copy-buffer size (in bytes)

            To copy files, Smarty requires a buffer. This tooltype allows
            you to specify the size of this buffer.

            The buffer size defaults to 100Kb, a reasonable value for any
            use (the 'Copy' command of the AmigaDOS uses this default
            value, too).

            I've made this value configurable 'cause I've been testing some
            buffer sizes in my A3000, and copy-speed can be significantly
            improved by making the buffer larger. An example: I copied a
            9.5Mb file from a dir to another in the same harddisk. With a
            buffer of 100Kb, the operation lasted 20s. Increasing the
            buffer size to 1Mb, the time used was 10s.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "INST" "Install"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}Installation@{ub}

     Simply double-click the english installation utility (Install.eng)
and follow the instructions.

     This way, Smarty will be copied into your SYS:, and then simply
copy it where you prefer.

     The english install script does nothing but copying the program
to SYS:.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "WHAT" "What's Smarty" @TOC "MAIN"

@{b}What's Smarty ?@{ub}

     Smarty is a little program that allows you to manipulate lists of
files, but it can't be considered a program like Dopus. It's oriented to
manipulate the files generated by a 3D program, or paint/animation program,
i.e., long lists of files, usually animations splitted in their images.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "REQU" "What do I need ?"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}What do I need ?@{ub}

     In order to execute Smarty, you need:

     -AmigaDOS v2.0+
     -MUI v3.2+

     AmigaOS v2.1+ (2.04) is required to use Locale.library. If you use
an AmigaOS prior to 2.04, Smarty will use the default english built-in
strings.

     The program has been tested on:

     A3000/25Mhz+18Mb RAM AmigaDOS 3.1
     A4000 68060_Cyberstormed & CyberVisioned
     A4000/040+12Mb RAM AmigaDOS 3.0
     A1200/030 28Mhz
     A1200/030 50Mhz

@ENDNODE

@NODE "HOWR" "How does it work ?"
@TOC "MAIN"

@{b}How does it work ?@{ub}

Note: But not very important. As any MUI app, Smarty ties itself to
      the system as a Commodity, so it can be controlled by Exchange or
      a similar program.

     The program has two main pages:

@{u} Directories @{uu}

     Here you have options to find the drawer your files are in.
     You can move through directories by double-clicking on the lists and
by using the 'Parent' and 'Root' buttons.

     Smarty's window is an 'AppWindow'. This means that you can drag a
Workbench icon on it. Smarty will then change the its current dir.

     'New Dir' allows you to create new directories.

     No further explanation required, I think.

@{u} Operation @{uu}

     Here you operate with the files.

          @{"     FILE LIST    " LINK "LIST"} 
                                         @{"   ALL     " LINK "BALL"}  
                                         @{"   NONE    " LINK "BNONE"}  
                                         @{"  TOGGLE   " LINK "BTOGGLE"}  
                                         @{" WILDCARD  " LINK "BWILD"}  
                                         @{"  SELECT   " LINK "BSELECT"}  
                                         @{"  STRETCH  " LINK "BSTRETCH"}  
                                         @{" ADJACENT  " LINK "BADJACENT"}  
                                         @{"   RANGE   " LINK "BRANGE"}  
       @{" Information                   " LINK "BINFO"}  

 HIDE:      @{"   SELECTED   " LINK "BHIDESEL"}@{" UNSELECTED " LINK "BHIDEUNSEL"}@{" UNHIDE ALL " LINK "BUNHIDE"}   
 FUNCTIONS: @{" DELETE " LINK "BDELETE"}@{" RENAME " LINK "BRENAME"}@{" COPY " LINK "BCOPY"}@{" MOVE " LINK "BMOVE"}@{" DUPLICATE " LINK "BDUP"}@{" VIEW " LINK "BVIEW"}   

@ENDNODE

@NODE "LIST" "List"
@TOC "MAIN"
File list

     This list contains the files in the drawer we have selected in the
directories page.

     Is a multi-select list.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BINFO" "Info"
@TOC "MAIN"
Information

     Here you have information about the number of files in the list, as
well as the number of selected entries.

     It also displays the current dir.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BALL" "ALL"
@TOC "MAIN"
ALL

     Selects all the files in the list.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BNONE" "NONE"
@TOC "MAIN"
NONE

     Deselects all the files in the list.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BTOGGLE" "Toggle"
@TOC "MAIN"
TOGGLE

     Changes the state (selected/deselected) of all the entries of the list.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BWILD" "WILDCARD"
@TOC "MAIN"
WILDCARD

     Uses the function MatchPattern() to (de)select the entries which
match a given pattern.

     The pattern can contain any AmigaDOS wildcard, for example:

     ?    -> Match a single character.
     #?   -> Match any number of characters.

     You can find information about wildcards in your AmigaDOS manual.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BSELECT" "SELECT"
@TOC "MAIN"
SELECT

     Allows "jump"-selection (or deselection) of files.

     For example:

          Select    1    every     10

     Will select file number 1, 11, 21, 31...

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BSTRETCH" "STRETCH"
@TOC "MAIN"
STRETCH

     In this function you specify the total number of files you want to be
selected. The program does the rest.

     Please remember:

     -'Final' must be always greater than two, as at least the first and
      last entries will be selected.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BADJACENT" "ADJACENT"
@TOC "MAIN"
ADJACENT

     This function selects the 'adjacent' file every selected entry.

     If you export an animation by fields (1 file=1 field), you can select
a whole frame ( 1 frame = 2 fields = 2 files) by only selecting a field
and then using this function.

     (clear enough ???)

     This function is useful when used together with Strech, for example.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BRANGE" "RANGE"
@TOC "MAIN"
RANGE

     'Range' selects the entries between two selected entries.

     Actually it works with more than two selected entries. Just try it with
four, six, eight selected entries (always an even number, of course).

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BHIDESEL" "HIDE SEL"
@TOC "MAIN"
HIDE SELECTED

     "Hides" all the selected entries in the list.
     A hidden entry is not considered by the program.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BHIDEUNSEL" "HIDE UNSEL"
@TOC "MAIN"
HIDE UNSELECTED

     "Hides" all the NON-selected entries in the list.
     A hidden entry is not considered by the program.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BUNHIDE" "UNHIDE ALL"
@TOC "MAIN"
UNHIDE ALL

     Re-reads the directory, unhidding all the entries.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BDELETE" "DELETE"
@TOC "MAIN"
DELETE

     Deletes all the selected entries.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BRENAME" "RENAME"
@TOC "MAIN"
RENAME

     Renames the selected entries. It requires some values:

     Base Name :    e.g. 'Pic.'
     Start Number:  The first number to be used when renaming.
     Numbers:       "Number of numbers" ( e.g. 3 = 001, 002... )
     Extension:     Extension to add at the end of the renamed files.
     Step:          For example 2: 001, 003, 005...
     Reverse Rename:Clear ?.

     Please remember:

     -Smarty does not add '.' automatically.

     -Numbers, extension and step have default values. No need to fill them
      if you don't want to.

     -In Reverse Rename, renaming will take place from 'Start Number' and
      downwards. Keep this in mind.

     -Smarty _*does not*_ check if names will "collide". Please make sure
      this will not happen.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BVIEW" "VIEW"
@TOC "MAIN"
VIEW

     'View' lets you to 'see' all selected files using your prefered
file viewer.

     This viewer is defined via 'ToolTypes' (see 'Tooltypes').

     For example, if you are using AmigaOS 3.0/3.1, you can use 'Multiview',
so you'll be able to see not only images, but texts and sounds also:

               'VIEWTOOL=sys:utilities/multiview screen'

     Smarty asks for confimation before viewing any file.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BCOPY" "COPY"
@TOC "MAIN"
COPY

     Copies all the selected entries to a drawer.

     An ASL requester is opened. It allows you to specify where do you
want the files to be copied in. You can create a new dir by simply
typing the name of a dir that doesn't exist. It will be then created.

     In v1.1, copying files is done through a built-in function. To
perform the copy a memory buffer is required. You can configure
the size of this buffer via Tooltypes.

     If Smarty fails to allocate the buffer, it complaints and quits.

Note: The copy buffer is only allocated while copying.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "BMOVE" "MOVE"
@TOC "MAIN"
MOVE

     Moves (copy & delete) all the selected entries.

     An ASL requester is opened. It allows you to specify where do you
want the files to be copied in. You can create a new dir by simply
typing the name of a dir that doesn't exist. It will be then created.

     This function requires a copy buffer. See 'Copy'.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "BDUP" "DUP"
@TOC "MAIN"
DUP

     It duplicates all the selected entries. You can create up to 999 copies
of each file.

     For example, the duplicates of 'Foo.jpg' will be 'Foo.jpg.001',
'Foo.jpg.002' and so...

     This function requires a copy buffer. See 'Copy'.

@ENDNODE

